# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: butanediol-fermentation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] Of the three stereoisomers, two are enantiomers (levo- and dextro-2,3-butanediol) and one is a meso compound.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] The enantiomeric pair have (2*R*, 3*R*) and (2*S*, 3*S*) configurations at carbons 2 and 3, while the meso compound has configuration (2*R*, 3*S*) or, equivalently, (2*S*, 3*R*).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] The isomer distribution depends on the stereochemistry of the epoxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] The meso isomer is used to combine with naphthalene-1,5-diisocyanate.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] The resulting polyurethane is called "Vulkollan".
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] The (2*R*,3*R*)-stereoisomer of 2,3-butanediol is produced by a variety of microorganisms in a process known as butanediol fermentation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] It is found naturally in cocoa butter, in the roots of *Ruta graveolens*, sweet corn, and in rotten mussels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] It is used in the resolution of carbonyl compounds in gas chromatography.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] During World War II research was done towards producing 2,3-butanediol by fermentation in order to produce 1,3-butadiene, the monomer of the polybutadiene used in a leading type of synthetic rubber.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] It can be derived from the fermentation of sugarcane molasses.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] Fermentative production of 2,3-butanediol from carbohydrates involves a network of biochemical reactions that can be manipulated to maximize production.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] 2,3-butanediol has been proposed as a rocket fuel that could be created on Mars by means of cyanobacteria and *E. coli*, shipped from Earth, working on resources available at the surface of Mars.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/2-3-butanediol] 2,3-Butanediol has been detected, in peppers, grape wine, anatidaes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] 2,3-**Butanediol fermentation** is anaerobic fermentation of glucose with 2,3-butanediol as one of the end products.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Butanediol fermentation is typical for the facultative anaerobes *Klebsiella* and *Enterobacter* and is tested for using the Voges–Proskauer (VP) test.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] There are other alternative strains that can be used, talked about in details in the Alternative Bacteria Strains section below.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] The metabolic function of 2,3-butanediol is not known, although some have speculated that it was an evolutionary advantage for these microorganisms to produce a neutral product that's less inhibitory than other partial oxidation products and doesn't reduce the pH as much as mixed acids.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] There are many important industrial applications that butanediol can be used for, including antifreeze, food additives, antiseptic, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] It also is produced naturally in various places of the environment.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] 2,3-butanediol fermentation produces smaller amounts of acid than mixed acid fermentation, and butanediol, ethanol, CO2 and H2 are the end products.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] While equal amounts of CO2 and H2 are created during mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation produces more than twice the amount of CO2 because the gases are not produced only by formate hydrogen lyase as they are in mixed acid fermentation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] 2,3 Butanediol is produced at varying levels in aerated fermentations as long as the dissolved oxygen level is limiting (i.e., the culture is trying to consume more oxygen than is available).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] The degree of oxygen limitation dictates the ratios of 2,3-butanediol to by-products produced.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] 2,3-butanediol has a variety of industrial applications and products it can produce.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] The levo isomer of butanediol has a low freezing point of −60 °C, which allows it to work as an antifreeze agent.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Through catalytic dehydrogenation, butanediol can form diacetyl.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Diacetyl is a food additive that can be used to add flavor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] 0.1% butanediol will kill most pathogenic bacteria due to its antiseptic properties.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Through esterification, forms of precursors of polyurethane foams are produced.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] These can be used in various applications, including in pharmaceuticals, cosmetics, lotions, ointments, and antiperspirants.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Butanediol itself even has applications in the pharmaceutical industry as a drug carrier.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Using mesophilic bacteria requires the fermentation process to occur below 40 °C, which can cause bacterial contamination due to the low temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] On the industrial scale, this requires sterilization steps which means a special facility must be built, more employees are needed to run this extra step, and more energy is consumed at the plant.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] A novel aerobic *Geobacillus* strain XT15 has been shown to produce 2,3-butanediol at a temperature between 45 and 55 °C.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] This higher temperature will avoid the risk of contamination because microorganisms that live in normal environments cannot reproduce above 45 °C.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] The *Geobacillus* strain XT15 is thermophilic, which allows it to be able to operate fermentation at this higher temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/butanediol-fermentation] Sterilization would not be necessary using this alternative strain making the manufacturing process more efficient and cost-effective.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] In chemistry, **dehydrogenation** is a chemical reaction that involves the removal of hydrogen, usually from an organic molecule.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Dehydrogenation is important, both as a useful reaction and a serious problem.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] At its simplest, it is a useful way of converting alkanes, which are relatively inert and thus low-valued, to alkenes, which are reactive and thus more valuable.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Alkenes are precursors to aldehydes (R−CH=O), alcohols (R−OH), polymers, and aromatics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] As a problematic reaction, the fouling and inactivation of many catalysts arises via coking, which is the dehydrogenative polymerization of organic substrates.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Enzymes that catalyze dehydrogenation are called dehydrogenases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Dehydrogenation processes are used extensively to produce aromatics in the petrochemical industry.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Such processes are highly endothermic and require temperatures of 500 °C and above.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Dehydrogenation also converts saturated fats to unsaturated fats.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] One of the largest scale dehydrogenation reactions is the production of styrene by dehydrogenation of ethylbenzene.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Typical dehydrogenation catalysts are based on iron(III) oxide, promoted by several percent potassium oxide or potassium carbonate.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] The cracking processes, especially fluid catalytic cracking and steam cracking, produce high-purity mono-olefins from paraffins.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Typical operating conditions use chromium (III) oxide catalyst at 500 °C.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Target products are propylene, butenes, and isopentane, etc.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] These simple compounds are important raw materials for the synthesis of polymers and gasoline additives.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Alcohols can be selectively dehydrogenated to give aldehydes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] This in employed in the industrial production of butanone and is important in the production of certain aroma compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Oxidative dehydrogenation (ODH) of n-butane is an alternative to classical dehydrogenation, steam cracking and fluid catalytic cracking processes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Formaldehyde is produced industrially by oxidative dehydrogenation of methanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] This reaction can also be viewed as a dehydrogenation using O2 as the acceptor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] The most common catalysts are silver metal, iron(III) oxide, iron molybdenum oxides [e.g. iron(III) molybdate] with a molybdenum-enriched surface, or vanadium oxides.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] In the commonly used formox process, methanol and oxygen react at ca.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] A variety of dehydrogenation processes have been described for organic compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] These dehydrogenation is of interest in the synthesis of fine organic chemicals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Such reactions often rely on transition metal catalysts.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Dehydrogenation of unfunctionalized alkanes can be effected by homogeneous catalysis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Especially active for this reaction are pincer complexes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] Dehydrogenation of amines to nitriles can be accomplished using a variety of reagents, such as iodine pentafluoride (IF 5).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] In typical aromatization, six-membered alicyclic rings, e.g. cyclohexene, can be aromatized in the presence of hydrogenation acceptors.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] The elements sulfur and selenium promote this process.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] On the laboratory scale, quinones, especially 2,3-dichloro-5,6-dicyano-1,4-benzoquinone (DDQ) are effective.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] The dehydrogenative coupling of silanes has also been developed.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] The dehydrogenation of amine-boranes is related reaction.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dehydrogenation] This process once gained interests for its potential for hydrogen storage.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] A distinctive feature of diacetyl (and other vicinal diketones) is the long C–C bond linking the carbonyl centers.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] This bond distance is about 1.54 Å, compared to 1.45 Å for the corresponding C–C bond in 1,3-butadiene.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] The elongation is attributed to repulsion between the polarized carbonyl carbon centers.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl arises naturally as a byproduct of fermentation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In some fermentative bacteria, it is formed via the thiamine pyrophosphate-mediated condensation of pyruvate and acetyl CoA.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Sour (cultured) cream, cultured buttermilk, and cultured butter are produced by inoculating pasteurized cream or milk with a lactic starter culture, churning (agitating) and holding the milk until a desired pH drop (or increase in acidity) is attained.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Cultured cream, cultured butter, and cultured buttermilk owe their tart flavour to lactic acid bacteria and their buttery aroma and taste to diacetyl.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Malic acid can be converted to lactic acid to make diacetyl.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl is produced industrially by dehydrogenation of 2,3-butanediol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl and acetoin are two compounds that give butter its characteristic taste.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Because of this, manufacturers of artificial butter flavoring, margarines or similar oil-based products typically add diacetyl and acetoin (along with beta-carotene for the yellow color) to make the final product butter-flavored, because it would otherwise be relatively tasteless.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl is used as a flavoring agent in some liquids used in electronic cigarettes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] People nearby may be exposed to it in the exhaled aerosol at levels near the limit set for occupational exposure.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In some styles of beer (e.g. in Czech lagers and many beer styles produced in the United Kingdom, such as stouts, English bitters, and Scottish ales), the presence of diacetyl can be acceptable or desirable at low or, in some cases, moderate levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In other styles, its presence is considered a flaw or undesirable.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl is produced during fermentation as a byproduct of valine synthesis, when yeast produces α-acetolactate, which escapes the cell and is spontaneously decarboxylated into diacetyl.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] The yeast then absorbs the diacetyl, and reduces the ketone groups to form acetoin and 2,3-butanediol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Beer sometimes undergoes a "diacetyl rest", in which its temperature is raised slightly for two or three days after fermentation is complete, to allow the yeast to absorb the diacetyl it produced earlier in the fermentation cycle.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] The makers of some wines, such as chardonnay, deliberately promote the production of diacetyl because of the feel and flavor it imparts.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Diacetyl is present in some chardonnays known as "butter bombs", although there is a trend back toward the more traditional French styles.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Concentrations from 0.005 mg/L to 1.7 mg/L were measured in chardonnay wines, and the amount needed for the flavor to be noticed is at least 0.2 mg/L.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] The European Commission has declared diacetyl is legal for use as a flavouring substance in all EU states.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] As a diketone, diacetyl is included in the EU's flavouring classification Flavouring Group Evaluation 11 (FGE.11).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] A Scientific Panel of the EU Commission evaluated six flavouring substances (not including diacetyl) from FGE.11 in 2004.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] As part of this study, the panel reviewed available studies on several other flavourings in FGE.11, including diacetyl.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Based on the available data, the panel reiterated the finding that there were no safety concerns for diacetyl's use as a flavouring.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In 2007, the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), the EU's food safety regulatory body, stated its scientific panel on food additives and flavourings (AFC) was evaluating diacetyl along with other flavourings as part of a larger study.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In 2007, the Flavor and Extract Manufacturers Association recommended reducing diacetyl in butter flavorings.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] Manufacturers of butter flavored popcorn including Pop Weaver, Trail's End, and ConAgra Foods (maker of Orville Redenbacher's and Act II) began removing diacetyl as an ingredient from their products.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] OSHA Safety and Health Information Bulletin and companion Worker Alert recommend employers use safety measures to minimize exposure to diacetyl or its substitutes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/diacetyl] In 2016, diacetyl was banned in e-liquids/e-cigarettes in the EU under the EU Tobacco Products Directive.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen gas was first produced artificially in the 17th century by the reaction of acids with metals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Henry Cavendish, in 1766–1781, identified hydrogen gas as a distinct substance and discovered its property of producing water when burned: this is the origin of hydrogen's name, which means 'water-former' (from Ancient Greek: ὕδωρ, romanized: *húdōr*, lit.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] 'water', and γεννάω, *gennáō*, 'I bring forth').
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Understanding the colors of light absorbed and emitted by hydrogen was a crucial part of the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen, typically nonmetallic except under extreme pressure, readily forms covalent bonds with most nonmetals, contributing to the formation of compounds like water and various organic substances.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Its role is crucial in acid–base reactions, which mainly involve proton exchange among soluble molecules.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In ionic compounds, hydrogen can take the form of either a negatively-charged anion, where it is known as hydride, or as a positively charged cation, H+, hydron.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Although tightly bonded to water molecules, hydrons strongly affect the behavior of aqueous solutions, as reflected in the importance of pH.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydride, on the other hand, is rarely observed because it tends to deprotonate solvents, yielding H2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the early universe, neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years after the Big Bang as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] After stars began to form, most of the hydrogen in the intergalactic medium was re-ionized.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Nearly all hydrogen production is done by transforming fossil fuels, particularly steam reforming of natural gas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It can also be produced from water or saline by electrolysis, but this process is more expensive.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Its main industrial uses include fossil fuel processing and ammonia production for fertilizer.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Emerging uses for hydrogen include the use of fuel cells to generate electricity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The ground state energy level of the electron in a hydrogen atom is −13.6 electronvolts (eV), equivalent to an ultraviolet photon of roughly 91 nanometers wavelength.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen are referred to by consecutive quantum numbers, with $n=1$ being the ground state.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The hydrogen spectral series corresponds to emission of light due to transitions from higher to lower energy levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Each energy level is further split by spin interactions between the electron and proton into four hyperfine levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] High-precision values for the hydrogen atom energy levels are required for definitions of physical constants.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Quantum calculations have identified nine contributions to the energy levels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The eigenvalue from the Dirac equation is the largest contribution.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Other terms include relativistic recoil, the self-energy, and the vacuum polarization terms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The standards organization for chemical names, IUPAC, gives general names when the context assumes natural isotope abundance or ignores the isotope.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These general names are *hydrogen* for the neutral atom, *hydron* for the cation, H+, *hydride* for the anion, and H-.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The name *proton* is often used for the positively charged cation, but this is strictly correct only for the cation of the dominant isotope 1 H.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen has three naturally-occurring isotopes, denoted 1 H, 2 H and 3 H.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Other, highly-unstable nuclides (4 H to 7 H) have been synthesized in laboratories but not observed in nature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Unique among the elements, distinct names are assigned to hydrogen's isotopes in common use.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] During the early study of radioactivity, heavy radioisotopes were given their own names, but these are mostly no longer used.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The symbols D and T (instead of 2 H and 3 H) are sometimes used for deuterium and tritium, but the symbol P was already used for phosphorus and thus was not available for protium.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In its nomenclatural guidelines, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) allows any of D, T, 2 H, and 3 H to be used, though 2 H and 3 H are preferred.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Antihydrogen (H) is the antimatter counterpart to hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It consists of an anti­proton with a positron.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The exotic atom muonium (symbol Mu), composed of an antimuon and an electron, is the anti­matter analogue of hydrogen; IUPAC nomenclature incorporates such hypothetical compounds as muonium chloride (MuCl) and sodium muonide (NaMu), analogous to hydrogen chloride and sodium hydride respectively.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Under standard conditions, hydrogen is a gas of diatomic molecules with the formula H2, officially called "dihydrogen", but also called "molecular hydrogen", or simply hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Dihydrogen is a colorless, odorless, flammable gas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The amount of heat released per mole of hydrogen is −286 kilojoules (kJ), or 141.9 megajoules (MJ) for a one-kilogram (2.2 lb) mass (based on the higher heating value measurement).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen gas forms explosive mixtures with air in concentrations from 4%–74% and with chlorine at 5%–95%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The hydrogen autoignition temperature, the temperature of spontaneous ignition in air, is 500 °C (932 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In a high-pressure hydrogen leak, the shock wave from the leak itself can heat air to the autoignition temperature, leading to flaming and possibly explosion.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen flames emit faint blue and ultraviolet light.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Flame detectors are used to detect hydrogen fires as they are nearly invisible to the naked eye in daylight.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Molecular H2 exists as two nuclear isomers that differ in the spin states of their nuclei.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the **ortho­hydrogen** form, the spins of the two nuclei are parallel, forming a spin triplet state having a total molecular spin $S=1$ ; in the **para­hydrogen** form the spins are anti­parallel and form a spin singlet state having spin $S=0$ .
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The equilibrium ratio of ortho- to para-hydrogen depends on temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] At room temperature or warmer, equilibrium hydrogen gas contains about 25% of the para form and 75% of the ortho form.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The ortho form is an excited state, having higher energy than the para form by 1.455 kJ/mol, and it converts to the para form over the course of several minutes when cooled to low temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The thermal properties of these isomers differ because each has distinct rotational quantum states.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The ortho-to-para ratio in H2 is an important consideration in the liquefaction and storage of liquid hydrogen: the conversion from ortho to para is exothermic, and produces sufficient heat to evaporate most of the liquid if the conversion to para­hydrogen does not occur during the cooling process.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Catalysts for the ortho-para inter­conversion, such as ferric oxide and activated carbon compounds, are therefore used during hydrogen cooling to avoid this loss of liquid.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Liquid hydrogen can exist at temperatures below hydrogen's critical point of 33 kelvins (−240.2 °C; −400.3 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] However, for it to be in a fully liquid state at atmospheric pressure, H2 needs to be cooled to 20.28 K (−252.87 °C; −423.17 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Liquid hydrogen becomes solid hydrogen at standard pressure below hydrogen's melting point of 14.01 K (−259.14 °C; −434.45 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Distinct solid phases exist, known as Phase I through Phase V, each exhibiting a characteristic molecular arrangement.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Liquid and solid phases can exist in combination at the triple point; this mixture is known as slush hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Metallic hydrogen, a phase obtained at extremely high pressures (in excess of 400 billion Pa (58,000,000 psi)), is an electrical conductor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It is believed to exist deep within giant planets like Jupiter.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] When ionized, hydrogen becomes a plasma.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This is the form in which hydrogen exists within stars.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In 1671, Irish scientist Robert Boyle discovered and described the reaction between iron filings and dilute acids, which results in the production of hydrogen gas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Boyle did not note that the gas was flammable, but hydrogen would play a key role in overturning the phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In 1766, Henry Cavendish was the first to recognize hydrogen gas as a discrete substance, by naming the gas from a metal-acid reaction "inflammable air".
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] He speculated that "inflammable air" was in fact identical to the hypothetical substance "phlogiston" and further finding in 1781 that the gas produces water when burned.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] He is usually given credit for the discovery of hydrogen as an element.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In 1783, Antoine Lavoisier identified the element that came to be known as hydrogen when he and Laplace reproduced Cavendish's finding that water is produced when hydrogen is burned.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Lavoisier produced hydrogen for his experiments on mass conservation by treating metallic iron with a stream of water through an incandescent iron tube heated in a fire.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Many metals react similarly with water, leading to the production of hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In some situations, this H2-producing process is problematic, for instance in the case of zirconium cladding on nuclear fuel rods.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] By 1806 hydrogen was used to fill balloons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] François Isaac de Rivaz built the first de Rivaz engine, an internal combustion engine powered by a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen, in 1806.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Edward Daniel Clarke invented the hydrogen gas blowpipe in 1819.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The Döbereiner's lamp and limelight were invented in 1823.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen was liquefied for the first time by James Dewar in 1898 by using regenerative cooling and his invention, the vacuum flask.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] He produced solid hydrogen the next year.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] According to quantum theory, this behavior arises from the spacing of the (quantized) rotational energy levels, which are particularly wide-spaced in H2 because of its low mass.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These widely-spaced levels inhibit equal partition of heat energy into rotational motion in hydrogen at low temperatures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Diatomic gases composed of heavier atoms do not have such widely spaced levels and do not exhibit the same effect.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The existence of the hydride anion was suggested by Gilbert N.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Lewis in 1916 for group 1 and group 2 salt-like compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In 1920, Moers electrolyzed molten lithium hydride (LiH), producing a stoichiometric quantity of hydrogen at the anode.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Because of its simple atomic structure, consisting only of a proton and an electron, the hydrogen atom, together with the spectrum of light produced from it or absorbed by it, has been central to the development of the theory of atomic structure.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The energy levels of hydrogen can be calculated fairly accurately using the Bohr model of the atom, in which the electron "orbits" the proton, just as Earth orbits the Sun.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] However, the electron and proton are held together by electrostatic attraction, while planets and celestial objects are held by gravity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Due to the discretization of angular momentum postulated in early quantum mechanics by Bohr, the electron in the Bohr model can only occupy certain allowed distances from the proton, and therefore only certain allowed energies.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen's unique position as the only neutral atom for which the Schrödinger equation can be directly solved has significantly contributed to the understanding of quantum mechanics through the exploration of its energetics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Furthermore, study of the corresponding simplicity of the hydrogen molecule and the corresponding cation, H+2, brought understanding of the nature of the chemical bond, which followed shortly after the quantum mechanical treatment of the hydrogen atom had been developed in the mid-1920s.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Because H2 has only 7% the density of air, it was once widely used as a lifting gas in balloons and airships.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The first hydrogen-filled balloon was invented by Jacques Charles in 1783.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen provided the lift for the first reliable form of air-travel following the 1852 invention of the first hydrogen-lifted airship by Henri Giffard.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] German count Ferdinand von Zeppelin promoted the idea of rigid airships lifted by hydrogen that later were called Zeppelins, the first of which had its maiden flight in 1900.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Regularly-scheduled flights started in 1910 and by the outbreak of World War I in August 1914, they had carried 35,000 passengers without a serious incident.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen-lifted airships in the form of blimps were used as observation platforms and bombers during World War II, especially on the US Eastern seaboard.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The first non-stop transatlantic crossing was made by the British airship *R34* in 1919 and regular passenger service resumed in the 1920s.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen was used in the *Hindenburg*, which caught fire over New Jersey on 6 May 1937.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The hydrogen that filled the airship was ignited, possibly by static electricity, and burst into flames.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Following this disaster, commercial hydrogen airship travel ceased.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is still used, in preference to non-flammable but more expensive helium, as a lifting gas for weather balloons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Deuterium was discovered in December 1931 by Harold Urey, and tritium was prepared in 1934 by Ernest Rutherford, Mark Oliphant, and Paul Harteck.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Heavy water, which consists of deuterium in the place of regular hydrogen, was discovered by Urey's group in 1932.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The thermodynamic basis of this low reactivity is the very strong H–H bond, with a bond dissociation energy of 435.7 kJ/mol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It does form coordination complexes called dihydrogen complexes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These species provide insights into the early steps in the interactions of hydrogen with metal catalysts.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] According to neutron diffraction, the metal and two H atoms form a triangle in these complexes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The H-H bond remains intact but is elongated.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Although exotic on Earth, the H+3 ion is common in the universe.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It is a triangular species, like the aforementioned dihydrogen complexes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It is known as protonated molecular hydrogen or the trihydrogen cation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen reacts with chlorine to produce HCl, and with bromine to produce HBr, via a chain reaction.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For example, in the case of Br2, the dibromine molecule is split apart: Br2 + (UV light) → 2Br•.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The addition of H2 to unsaturated organic compounds, such as alkenes and alkynes, is called hydrogenation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Even if the reaction is energetically favorable, it does not occur spontaneously even at higher temperatures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the presence of a catalyst like finely divided platinum or nickel, the reaction proceeds at room temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen can exist in both +1 and −1 oxidation states, forming compounds through ionic and covalent bonding.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The element is part of a wide range of substances, including water, hydrocarbons, and numerous other organic compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The H+ ion—commonly referred to as a proton due to its single proton and absence of electrons—is central to acid–base chemistry, although the proton does not move freely.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the Brønsted–Lowry framework, acids are defined by their ability to donate H+ ions to bases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen forms a vast variety of compounds with carbon, known as hydrocarbons, and an even greater diversity with other elements (heteroatoms), giving rise to the broad class of organic compounds often associated with living organisms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen compounds with hydrogen in the oxidation state −1 are known as hydrides, which are usually formed between hydrogen and metals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The hydrides can be ionic (aka saline), covalent, or metallic.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] With heating, H2 reacts efficiently with the alkali and alkaline earth metals to give the ionic hydrides of the formulas MH and MH2, respectively.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These salt-like crystalline compounds have high melting points and all react with water to liberate hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Covalent hydrides include boranes and polymeric aluminium hydride.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Transition metals form metal hydrides via continuous dissolution of hydrogen into the metal.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] A well-known hydride is lithium aluminium hydride: the [AlH4]− anion carries hydridic centers firmly attached to the Al(III).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Perhaps the most extensive series of hydrides are the boranes, compounds consisting only of boron and hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrides can bond to these electropositive elements not only as a terminal ligand but also as bridging ligands.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In diborane (B2H6), four hydrogen atoms are terminal, while two bridge between the two boron atoms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] When bonded to a more electronegative element, particularly fluorine, oxygen, or nitrogen, hydrogen can participate in a form of medium-strength noncovalent bonding with another electronegative element with a lone pair like oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This phenomenon, called hydrogen bonding, is critical to the stability of many biological molecules.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen bonding alters molecule structures, viscosity, solubility, melting and boiling points, and even protein folding dynamics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In water, hydrogen bonding plays an important role in reaction thermodynamics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] A hydrogen bond can shift over to proton transfer.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Under the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, acids are proton donors, while bases are proton acceptors.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] A bare proton (H+) essentially cannot exist in anything other than a vacuum.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Otherwise it attaches to other atoms, ions, or molecules.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Even chemical species as inert as methane can be protonated.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The term "proton" is used loosely and metaphorically to refer to solvated hydrogen cations attached to other chemical species; it is denoted "H+" without any implication that any single protons exist freely in solution as a species.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] To avoid the implication of the naked proton in solution, acidic aqueous solutions are sometimes considered to contain the "hydronium ion" ([H3O]+), or still more accurately, [H9O4]+.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Other oxonium ions are found when water is in acidic solution with other solvents.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The concentration of these solvated protons determines the pH of a solution, a logarithmic scale that reflects its acidity or basicity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Lower pH values indicate higher concentrations of hydronium ions, corresponding to more acidic conditions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen, as atomic H, is the most abundant chemical element in the universe, making up 75% of normal matter by mass. and >90% by number of atoms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the early universe, protons formed in the first second after the Big Bang; neutral hydrogen atoms formed about 370,000 years later during the recombination epoch as the universe expanded and plasma had cooled enough for electrons to remain bound to protons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In astrophysics, neutral hydrogen in the interstellar medium is called *H I* and ionized hydrogen is called *H II*.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Radiation from stars ionizes H I to H II, creating spheres of ionized H II around stars.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the chronology of the universe neutral hydrogen dominated until the birth of stars during the era of reionization, which then produced bubbles of ionized hydrogen that grew and merged over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These are the source of the 21-centimeter hydrogen line, at 1420 MHz, that is detected in order to probe primordial hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The large amount of neutral hydrogen found in the damped Lyman-alpha systems is thought to dominate the cosmological baryonic density of the universe up to a redshift of *z* = 4.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is found in great abundance in stars and gas giant planets.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Molecular clouds of H2 are associated with star formation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen plays a vital role in powering stars through the proton-proton reaction in lower-mass stars, and through the CNO cycle of nuclear fusion in stars more massive than the Sun.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Protonated molecular hydrogen (H+3) is found in the interstellar medium, where it is generated by ionization of molecular hydrogen by cosmic rays.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This ion has also been observed in the upper atmosphere of Jupiter.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The ion is long-lived in outer space due to the low temperature and density.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] H+3 is one of the most abundant ions in the universe, and it plays a notable role in the chemistry of the interstellar medium.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Neutral triatomic hydrogen H3 can exist only in an excited form and is unstable.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is the third most abundant element on the Earth's surface, mostly existing within chemical compounds such as hydrocarbons and water.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Elemental hydrogen is normally in the form of a gas, H2, at standard conditions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It is present in a very low concentration in Earth's atmosphere (around 0.53 parts per million on a molar basis) because of its light weight, which enables it to escape the atmosphere more rapidly than heavier gases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Despite its low concentration in the atmosphere, terrestrial hydrogen is sufficiently abundant to support the metabolism of several varieties of bacteria.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Large underground deposits of hydrogen gas have been discovered in several countries including Mali, France and Australia.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] As of 2024, it is uncertain how much underground hydrogen can be extracted economically.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Nearly all of the world's current supply of hydrogen gas (H2) is produced from fossil fuels, with less than 1% of hydrogen being produced by low-emissions technologies in 2025.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Many methods exist for producing H2, but three dominate commercially: steam reforming often coupled to water-gas shift, partial oxidation of hydrocarbons, and water electrolysis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is mainly produced by steam methane reforming (SMR), the reaction of water and methane.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Producing one tonne of hydrogen through this process emits 6.6–9.3 tonnes of carbon dioxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The production of natural gas feedstock also produces emissions such as vented and fugitive methane, which further contributes to the overall carbon footprint of hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This reaction is favored at low pressures but is nonetheless conducted at high pressures (2.0 MPa [20 atm; 590 inHg]) because high-pressure H2 is the most marketable product, and pressure swing adsorption (PSA) purification systems work better at higher pressures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The product mixture is known as "synthesis gas" because it is often used directly for the production of methanol and many other compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrocarbons other than methane can be used to produce synthesis gas with varying product ratios.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Therefore, steam reforming typically employs an excess of H2O.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Additional hydrogen can be recovered from the steam by using carbon monoxide through the water gas shift reaction (WGS).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is sometimes produced and consumed in the same industrial process, without being separated.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the Haber process for ammonia production, hydrogen is generated from natural gas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Olefin production units may produce substantial quantities of byproduct hydrogen, particularly from cracking light feedstocks like ethane or propane.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Electrolysis of water is a conceptually simple method of producing hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Commercial electrolyzers use nickel-based catalysts in strongly alkaline solution.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Platinum is a better catalyst but is expensive.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The hydrogen created through electrolysis using renewable energy is commonly referred to as "green hydrogen".
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Electrolysis of brine to yield chlorine also produces high-purity hydrogen as a co-product, which is used for a variety of transformations such as hydrogenations.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The electrolysis process is more expensive than producing hydrogen from methane without carbon capture and storage.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Innovation in hydrogen electrolyzers could make large-scale production of hydrogen from electricity more cost-competitive.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The carbon may be sold as a manufacturing feedstock or fuel, or landfilled.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This route could have a lower carbon footprint than existing hydrogen production processes, but mechanisms for removing the carbon and preventing it from reacting with the catalyst remain obstacles for industrial-scale use.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Water splitting is the process by which water is decomposed into its components.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The reaction occurs in the light-dependent reactions in all photosynthetic organisms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] A few organisms, including the alga *Chlamydomonas reinhardtii* and cyanobacteria, have evolved a second step in the dark reactions in which protons and electrons are reduced to form H2 gas by specialized hydrogenases in the chloroplast.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Efforts have been undertaken to genetically modify cyanobacterial hydrogenases to more efficiently generate H2 gas even in the presence of oxygen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Efforts have also been undertaken with genetically‐modified alga in a bioreactor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Over 200 thermochemical cycles can be used for water splitting.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] A number of labs (including in France, Germany, Greece, Japan, and the United States) are developing thermochemical methods to produce hydrogen from solar energy and water.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] H2 is produced in organisms by enzymes called hydrogenases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This process allows the host organism to use fermentation as a source of energy.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These same enzymes also can oxidize H2, such that the host organisms can subsist by reducing oxidized substrates using electrons extracted from H2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogenase enzymes feature iron or iron–nickel centers at their active sites.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The natural cycle of hydrogen production and consumption by organisms is called the hydrogen cycle.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Some bacteria such as *Mycobacterium smegmatis* can use the small amount of hydrogen in the atmosphere as a source of energy when other sources are lacking.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Their hydrogenases feature small channels that exclude oxygen from the active site, permitting the reaction to occur even though the hydrogen concentration is very low and the oxygen concentration is as in normal air.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Confirming the existence of hydrogenase‐employing microbes in the human gut, H2 occurs in human breath.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The concentration in the breath of fasting people at rest is typically under 5 parts per million (ppm), but can reach 50 ppm when people with intestinal disorders consume molecules they cannot absorb during diagnostic hydrogen breath tests.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Serpentinization is a geological mechanism which produces highly-reducing conditions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This process also is relevant to the corrosion of iron and steel in oxygen-free groundwater and in reducing soils below the water table.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is also often a by-product of other reactions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Many metals react with water to produce H2, but the rate of hydrogen evolution depends on the metal, the pH, and the presence of alloying agents.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Most often, hydrogen evolution is induced by acids.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The alkali and alkaline earth metals as well as aluminium, zinc, manganese, and iron, react readily with aqueous acids.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Many metals, such as aluminium, are slow to react with water because they form passivated oxide coatings.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] An alloy of aluminium and gallium, however, does react with water.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] If H2 is to be used as an energy source, its storage is important.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For example, at room temperature and 0.1 millipascals (9.9×10−10 atm), approx.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] 0.05 moles of hydrogen dissolve into one kilogram (2.2 lb) of diethyl ether.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] H2 can be stored in compressed form, although compressing costs energy.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Liquefaction is impractical given hydrogen's low critical temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In contrast, ammonia and many hydrocarbons can be liquified at room temperature under pressure.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For these reasons, hydrogen *carriers*—materials that reversibly bind H2—have attracted much attention.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The key question is then the weight percent of H2-equivalents within the carrier material.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For example, hydrogen can be reversibly absorbed into many rare earths and transition metals and is soluble in both nanocrystalline and amorphous metals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen solubility in metals is influenced by local distortions or impurities in the crystal lattice.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] These properties may be useful when hydrogen is purified by passage through hot palladium disks, but the gas's high solubility is also a metallurgical problem, contributing to the embrittlement of many metals, complicating the design of pipelines and storage tanks.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The most problematic aspect of metal hydrides for storage is their modest H2 content, often on the order of 1%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For this reason, there is interest in storage of H2 in compounds of low molecular weight.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For example, ammonia borane (H3N−BH3) contains 19.8 weight percent of H2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The problem with this material is that after release of H2, the resulting boron nitride does not re-add H2: i.e., ammonia borane is an irreversible hydrogen carrier.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Large quantities of H2 are used in the "upgrading" of fossil fuels.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Key consumers of H2 include hydrodesulfurization and hydrocracking.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Many of these reactions can be classified as hydrogenolysis, i.e., the cleavage of bonds by hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogenation, the addition of H2 to various substrates, is done on a large scale.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] This process consumes a few percent of the energy budget in the entire industry and is the biggest consumer of hydrogen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The resulting ammonia is used extensively in fertilizer production; these fertilizers have become essential feedstocks in modern agriculture.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogenation is also used to convert unsaturated fats and oils to saturated fats and oils.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The major application is the production of margarine.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Methanol is produced by hydrogenation of carbon dioxide; the mixture of hydrogen and carbon dioxide used for this process is known as syngas.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It is similarly the source of hydrogen in the manufacture of hydrochloric acid.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] H2 is also used as a reducing agent for the conversion of some ores to the metals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The potential for using hydrogen (H2) as a fuel has been widely discussed.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen can be used in fuel cells to produce electricity, or burned to generate heat.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] When hydrogen is consumed in fuel cells, the only emission at the point of use is water vapor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] When burned, hydrogen produces relatively little pollution at the point of combustion, but can lead to thermal formation of harmful nitrogen oxides.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] If hydrogen is produced with low or zero greenhouse gas emissions (green hydrogen), it can play a significant role in decarbonizing energy systems where there are challenges and limitations to replacing fossil fuels with direct use of electricity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen fuel can produce the intense heat required for industrial production of steel, cement, glass, and chemicals, thus contributing to the decarbonization of industry alongside other technologies, such as electric arc furnaces for steelmaking.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] However, it is likely to play a larger role in providing industrial feedstock for cleaner production of ammonia and organic chemicals.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen used to decarbonize transportation is likely to find its largest applications in shipping, aviation and, to a lesser extent, heavy goods vehicles, through the use of hydrogen-derived synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol and fuel cell technology.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] For light-duty vehicles including cars, hydrogen is far behind other alternative fuel vehicles, especially compared with the rate of adoption of battery electric vehicles, and may not play a significant role in future.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen together serve as cryogenic propellants in liquid-propellant rockets, as in the Space Shuttle main engines.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] NASA has investigated the use of rocket propellant made from atomic hydrogen, boron or carbon that is frozen into solid molecular hydrogen particles suspended in liquid helium.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Upon warming, the mixture vaporizes to allow the atomic species to recombine, heating the mixture to high temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen produced when there is a surplus of variable renewable electricity could in principle be stored and later used to generate heat or to re-generate electricity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] It can be further transformed into synthetic fuels such as ammonia and methanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Disadvantages of hydrogen fuel include high costs of storage and distribution due to hydrogen's explosivity, its large volume compared to other fuels, and its tendency to embrittle materials.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The economic disadvantage of distribution can be reduced by co-locating facilities that use hydrogen in mining industry hubs.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The very long-lived, rechargeable nickel–hydrogen battery developed for satellite power systems uses pressurized gaseous H2.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The International Space Station, Mars Odyssey and the Mars Global Surveyor are equipped with nickel-hydrogen batteries.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In the dark part of its orbit, the Hubble Space Telescope is also powered by nickel-hydrogen batteries, which were finally replaced in May 2009, more than 19 years after launch and 13 years beyond their design life.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is employed in semiconductor manufacturing to saturate broken ("dangling") bonds of amorphous silicon and amorphous carbon, which helps in stabilizing the materials' properties.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen, introduced as an unintended side-effect of production, acts as a shallow electron donor leading to n-type conductivity in ZnO, with important uses in transducers and phosphors.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Detailed analysis of ZnO and of MgO shows evidence of four and six-fold hydrogen multicentre bonds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] The doping behavior of hydrogen varies with material.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In hydrogen pipelines and steel storage vessels, hydrogen molecules are prone to reacting with metals, causing hydrogen embrittlement and leaks in the pipeline or storage vessel.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Since it is lighter than air, hydrogen does not easily accumulate to form a combustible gas mixture.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] However, even without ignition sources, high-pressure hydrogen leakage may cause spontaneous combustion and detonation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is flammable when mixed even in small amounts with air.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Ignition can occur at a volumetric ratio of hydrogen to air as low as 4%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] In approximately 70% of hydrogen ignition accidents, the ignition source cannot be determined.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen fire, while being extremely hot, is almost invisible to the human eye, and thus can lead to accidental burns.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/dihydrogen] Hydrogen is non-toxic, but like most gases it can cause asphyxiation in the absence of adequate ventilation.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] One clinically important species from this genus is *E. cloacae*.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] In 2018, researchers detected five strains of *Enterobacter bugandensis* aboard the International Space Station (ISS) (none pathogenic to humans) and concluded that microbial populations on the ISS should be closely monitored to ensure a medically safe environment for astronauts.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] The genus *Enterobacter* ferments lactose with gas production during a 48-hour incubation at 35-37 °C in the presence of bile salts and detergents.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] It is oxidase-negative, indole-negative, and urease-variable.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] For *Enterobacter* species, flagella are used for adhesion, biofilm formation, and protein export as well as motility.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] The lipopolysaccharide capsule of *Enterobacter* spp. helps members of this genus avoid phagocytosis and initiate the host inflammatory response.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Pathogenic strains of *Enterobacter* spp. have been found in the sputum, blood, wounds, and stool of humans.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] *Enterobacter* spp. are associated with common nosocomial infections including respiratory, endocarditis, bacteremia, urinary tract infections, osteomyelitis, among others.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] *Enterobacter*-associated bacteremia presents as fever but can progress to systemic inflammatory response syndrome and shock.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] For pneumonia caused by *Enterobacter* spp., symptoms include coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Treatment is dependent on local trends of antibiotic resistance.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] *Enterobacter huaxiensis* and *Enterobacter chuandaensis* are two recently discovered species that exhibit especially antibiotic resistant characteristics.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Cefepime, a fourth-generation cephalosporin from the β-Lactam antibiotic class.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Imipenem (a carbapenem) is often the antibiotic of choice.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Aminoglycosides such as amikacin have been found to be very effective, as well.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Quinolones can be an effective alternative.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] A 2012 study has shown that the presence of *Enterobacter cloacae* B29 in the gut of a morbidly obese individual may have contributed to the patient's obesity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Reduction of the bacterial load within the patient's gut, from 35% *E. cloacae* B29 to non-detectable levels, was associated with a parallel reduction in endotoxin load in the patient and a concomitant, significant reduction in weight.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] Furthermore, the same bacterial strain, isolated from the patient, induced obesity and insulin resistance in germfree C57BL/6J mice that were being fed a high-fat diet.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/enterobacter] The study concludes that *E. cloacae* B29 may contribute to obesity in its human hosts through an endotoxin-induced, inflammation-mediated mechanism.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is naturally produced by the fermentation process of sugars by yeasts or via petrochemical processes such as ethylene hydration.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Historically it was used as a general anesthetic, and has modern medical applications as an antiseptic, disinfectant, solvent for some medications, and antidote for methanol poisoning and ethylene glycol poisoning.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It is used as a chemical solvent and in the synthesis of organic compounds, and as a fuel source for lamps, stoves, and internal combustion engines.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol also can be dehydrated to make ethylene, an important chemical feedstock.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] As of 2023, world production of ethanol fuel was 112.0 gigalitres (2.96×1010 US gallons), coming mostly from the U.S.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The term "ethanol", originates from the ethyl group coined in 1834 and was officially adopted in 1892, while "alcohol"—now referring broadly to similar compounds—originally described a powdered cosmetic and only later came to mean ethanol specifically.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol occurs naturally as a byproduct of yeast metabolism in environments like overripe fruit and palm blossoms, during plant germination under anaerobic conditions, in interstellar space, in human breath, and in rare cases, is produced internally due to auto-brewery syndrome.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol has been used since ancient times as an intoxicant.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Production through fermentation and distillation evolved over centuries across various cultures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Chemical identification and synthetic production began by the 19th century.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The "eth-" prefix and the qualifier "ethyl" in "ethyl alcohol" originally came from the name "ethyl" assigned in 1834 to the group C 2H 5− by Justus Liebig.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] He coined the word from the German name *Aether* of the compound C 2H 5−O−C 2H 5 (commonly called "ether" in English, more specifically called "diethyl ether").
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] According to the *Oxford English Dictionary*, *Ethyl* is a contraction of the Ancient Greek αἰθήρ (**aithḗr**, "upper air") and the Greek word ὕλη (**hýlē**, "wood, raw material", hence "matter, substance").
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] *Ethanol* was coined as a result of a resolution on naming alcohols and phenols that was adopted at the International Conference on Chemical Nomenclature that was held in April 1892 in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The term *alcohol* now refers to a wider class of substances in chemistry nomenclature, but in common parlance it remains the name of ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It is a medieval loan from Arabic *al-kuḥl*, a powdered ore of antimony used since antiquity as a cosmetic, and retained that meaning in Middle Latin.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The use of 'alcohol' for ethanol (in full, "alcohol of wine") was first recorded in 1753.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Before the late 18th century the term *alcohol* generally referred to any sublimated substance.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] As a central nervous system depressant, ethanol is one of the most commonly consumed psychoactive drugs.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Despite alcohol's psychoactive, addictive, and carcinogenic properties, it is readily available and legal for sale in many countries.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] There are laws regulating the sale, exportation/importation, taxation, manufacturing, consumption, and possession of alcoholic beverages.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The most common regulations are excise, and prohibition for minors.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] In mammals, ethanol is primarily metabolized in the liver and stomach by ADH enzymes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] When present in significant concentrations, this metabolism of ethanol is additionally aided by the cytochrome P450 enzyme CYP2E1 in humans, while trace amounts are also metabolized by catalase.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The resulting intermediate, acetaldehyde, is a known carcinogen, and poses significantly greater toxicity in humans than ethanol itself.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Many of the symptoms typically associated with alcohol intoxication—as well as many of the health hazards typically associated with the long-term consumption of ethanol—can be attributed to acetaldehyde toxicity in humans.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The subsequent oxidation of acetaldehyde into acetate is performed by aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) enzymes.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] This mutation is typically accompanied by another mutation in the ADH enzyme ADH1B in roughly 80% of east Asians, which improves the catalytic efficiency of converting ethanol into acetaldehyde.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is the oldest known sedative, used as an oral general anesthetic during surgery in ancient Mesopotamia and in medieval times.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Mild intoxication starts at a blood alcohol concentration of 0.03 – 0.05% and induces anesthetic coma at 0.4%.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] This use carries the high risk of deadly alcohol intoxication, pulmonary aspiration and vomiting, which led to use of alternatives in antiquity, such as opium and cannabis, and later diethyl ether, starting in the 1840s.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is used as an antiseptic in medical wipes and hand sanitizer gels for its bactericidal and anti-fungal effects.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol kills microorganisms by dissolving their membrane lipid bilayer and denaturing their proteins, and is effective against most bacteria, fungi and viruses.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It is ineffective against bacterial spores, which can be treated with hydrogen peroxide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] A solution of 70% ethanol is more effective than pure ethanol because ethanol relies on water molecules for optimal antimicrobial activity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Absolute ethanol may inactivate microbes without destroying them because the alcohol is unable to fully permeate the microbe's membrane.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol can also be used as a disinfectant and antiseptic by inducing cell dehydration through disruption of the osmotic balance across the cell membrane, causing water to leave the cell, leading to cell death.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol may be administered as an antidote to ethylene glycol poisoning and methanol poisoning.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It does so by acting as a competitive inhibitor against methanol and ethylene glycol for alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Though it has more side effects, ethanol is less expensive and more readily available than fomepizole in the role.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is used to dissolve many water-insoluble medications and related compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Liquid preparations of pain medications, cough and cold medicines, and mouth washes, for example, may contain up to 25% ethanol and may need to be avoided in individuals with adverse reactions to ethanol such as alcohol-induced respiratory reactions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is present mainly as an antimicrobial preservative in over 700 liquid preparations of medicine including acetaminophen, iron supplements, ranitidine, furosemide, mannitol, phenobarbital, trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole and over-the-counter cough medicine.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Some medicinal solutions of ethanol are also known as tinctures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The largest single use of ethanol is as an engine fuel and fuel additive.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Brazil in particular relies heavily upon the use of ethanol as an engine fuel, due in part to its role as one of the world's leading producers of ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Gasoline sold in Brazil contains at least 25% anhydrous ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Hydrous ethanol (about 95% ethanol and 5% water) can be used as fuel in more than 90% of new gasoline-fueled cars sold in the country.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The US and many other countries primarily use E10 (10% ethanol, sometimes known as gasohol) and E85 (85% ethanol) ethanol/gasoline mixtures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Over time, it is believed that a material portion of the ≈150-billion-US-gallon (570,000,000 m3) per year market for gasoline will begin to be replaced with fuel ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Australian law limits the use of pure ethanol from sugarcane waste to 10% in automobiles.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Older cars (and vintage cars designed to use a slower burning fuel) should have the engine valves upgraded or replaced.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] According to an industry advocacy group, ethanol as a fuel reduces harmful tailpipe emissions of carbon monoxide, particulate matter, oxides of nitrogen, and other ozone-forming pollutants.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Argonne National Laboratory analyzed greenhouse gas emissions of many different engine and fuel combinations, and found that biodiesel/petrodiesel blend (B20) showed a reduction of 8%, conventional E85 ethanol blend a reduction of 17% and cellulosic ethanol 64%, compared with pure gasoline.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol has a much greater research octane number (RON) than gasoline, meaning it is less prone to pre-ignition, allowing for better ignition advance which means more torque, and efficiency in addition to the lower carbon emissions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol combustion in an internal combustion engine yields many of the products of incomplete combustion produced by gasoline and significantly larger amounts of formaldehyde and related species such as acetaldehyde.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] This leads to a significantly larger photochemical reactivity and more ground level ozone.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] This data has been assembled into The Clean Fuels Report comparison of fuel emissions and show that ethanol exhaust generates 2.14 times as much ozone as gasoline exhaust.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] When this is added into the custom *Localized Pollution Index* of The Clean Fuels Report, the local pollution of ethanol (pollution that contributes to smog) is rated 1.7, where gasoline is 1.0 and higher numbers signify greater pollution.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The California Air Resources Board formalized this issue in 2008 by recognizing control standards for formaldehydes as an emissions control group, much like the conventional NOx and reactive organic gases (ROGs).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] More than 20% of Brazilian cars are able to use 100% ethanol as fuel, which includes ethanol-only engines and flex-fuel engines.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Flex-fuel engines in Brazil are able to work with all ethanol, all gasoline or any mixture of both.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] In the United States, flex-fuel vehicles can run on 0% to 85% ethanol (15% gasoline) since higher ethanol blends are not yet allowed or efficient.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Brazil supports this fleet of ethanol-burning automobiles with large national infrastructure that produces ethanol from domestically grown sugarcane.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The Indian government has heavily promoted Ethanol blending, recently approving E100 for the first time.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol's high miscibility with water makes it unsuitable for shipping through modern pipelines like liquid hydrocarbons.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Mechanics have seen increased cases of damage to small engines (in particular, the carburetor) and attribute the damage to the increased water retention by ethanol in fuel.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol was commonly used as fuel in early bipropellant rocket (liquid-propelled) vehicles, in conjunction with an oxidizer such as liquid oxygen.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The German A-4 ballistic rocket of World War II (better known by its propaganda name V-2), which is credited as having begun the space age, used ethanol as the main constituent of *B-Stoff*.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Under such nomenclature, the ethanol was mixed with 25% water to reduce the combustion chamber temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The V-2's design team helped develop U.S. rockets following World War II, including the ethanol-fueled Redstone rocket, which launched the first U.S. astronaut on suborbital spaceflight.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Alcohols fell into general disuse as more energy-dense rocket fuels were developed, although ethanol was used in recent experimental lightweight rocket-powered racing aircraft.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Commercial fuel cells operate on reformed natural gas, hydrogen or methanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is an attractive alternative due to its wide availability, low cost, high purity and low toxicity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] There is a wide range of fuel cell concepts that have entered trials including direct-ethanol fuel cells, auto-thermal reforming systems and thermally integrated systems.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The majority of work is being conducted at a research level although there are a number of organizations at the beginning of the commercialization of ethanol fuel cells.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol fireplaces can be used for home heating or for decoration.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol can also be used as stove fuel for cooking.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is an important industrial ingredient with widespread uses as a precursor for other organic compounds such as ethyl halides, ethyl esters, diethyl ether, acetic acid, and ethyl amines.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] As ethanol also has a low boiling point, it is easy to remove from a solution that has been used to dissolve other compounds, making it a popular extracting agent for botanical oils.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is found in paints, tinctures, markers, personal care products such as mouthwashes, perfumes and deodorants, and wet specimen preservatives.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Polysaccharides precipitate from aqueous solution in the presence of alcohol, and ethanol precipitation is used for this reason in the purification of DNA and RNA.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Because of its low freezing point of −114 °C (−173 °F) and low toxicity, ethanol is sometimes used in laboratories (with dry ice or other coolants) as a cooling bath to keep vessels at temperatures below the freezing point of water.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] For the same reason, it is also used as the active fluid in alcohol thermometers.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is also used in removing several stains, as it is considered a universal solvent.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Its molecular structure allows for the dissolving of both polar, hydrophilic and nonpolar, hydrophobic compounds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It can be used to dissolve oils, inks, and other substances.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The structure of the molecule of ethanol is CH3−CH2−OH (an ethyl group linked to a hydroxyl group), which indicates that the carbon of a methyl group (−CH3) is attached to the carbon of a methylene group (−CH2−), which is attached to the oxygen of a hydroxyl group (−OH).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It is a constitutional isomer of dimethyl ether.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is sometimes abbreviated as **EtOH**, using the common organic chemistry notation of representing the ethyl group (−CH2CH3) with **Et**.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is a volatile, colorless liquid that has a slight odor.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It burns with a smokeless blue flame that is not always visible in normal light.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The physical properties of ethanol stem primarily from the presence of its hydroxyl group and the shortness of its carbon chain.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol's hydroxyl group is able to participate in hydrogen bonding, rendering it more viscous and less volatile than less polar organic compounds of similar molecular weight, such as propane.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol's adiabatic flame temperature for combustion in air is 2082 °C or 3779 °F.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is slightly more refractive than water, having a refractive index of 1.36242 (at λ=589.3 nm and 18.35 °C or 65.03 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The triple point for ethanol is 150 ± 20 K.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is a versatile solvent, miscible with water and with many organic solvents, including acetic acid, acetone, benzene, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform, diethyl ether, ethylene glycol, glycerol, nitromethane, pyridine, and toluene.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Its main use as a solvent is in making tincture of iodine, cough syrups, etc.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] It is also miscible with light aliphatic hydrocarbons, such as pentane and hexane, and with aliphatic chlorides such as trichloroethane and tetrachloroethylene.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol's miscibility with water contrasts with the immiscibility of longer-chain alcohols (five or more carbon atoms), whose water miscibility decreases sharply as the number of carbons increases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The miscibility of ethanol with alkanes is limited to alkanes up to undecane: mixtures with dodecane and higher alkanes show a miscibility gap below a certain temperature (about 13 °C for dodecane).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The miscibility gap tends to get wider with higher alkanes, and the temperature for complete miscibility increases.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol-water mixtures have less volume than the sum of their individual components at the given fractions.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Mixing equal volumes of ethanol and water results in only 1.92 volumes of mixture.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Mixing ethanol and water is exothermic, with up to 777 J/mol being released at 298 K.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Hydrogen bonding causes pure ethanol to be hygroscopic to the extent that it readily absorbs water from the air.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The polar nature of the hydroxyl group causes ethanol to dissolve many ionic compounds, notably sodium and potassium hydroxides, magnesium chloride, calcium chloride, ammonium chloride, ammonium bromide, and sodium bromide.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Sodium and potassium chlorides are slightly soluble in ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Because the ethanol molecule also has a nonpolar end, it will also dissolve nonpolar substances, including most essential oils and numerous flavoring, coloring, and medicinal agents.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The addition of even a few percent of ethanol to water sharply reduces the surface tension of water.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] This property partially explains the "tears of wine" phenomenon.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] When wine is swirled in a glass, ethanol evaporates quickly from the thin film of wine on the wall of the glass.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] As the wine's ethanol content decreases, its surface tension increases and the thin film "beads up" and runs down the glass in channels rather than as a smooth sheet.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] At atmospheric pressure, mixtures of ethanol and water form an azeotrope at about 89.4 mol% ethanol (95.6% ethanol by mass, 97% alcohol by volume), with a boiling point of 351.3 K (78.2 °C; 172.7 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] At lower pressure, the composition of the ethanol-water azeotrope shifts to more ethanol-rich mixtures.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The minimum-pressure azeotrope has an ethanol fraction of 100% and a boiling point of 306 K (33 °C; 91 °F), corresponding to a pressure of roughly 70 torr (9.333 kPa).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Below this pressure, there is no azeotrope, and it is possible to distill absolute ethanol from an ethanol-water mixture.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] An ethanol–water solution will catch fire if heated above a temperature called its flash point and an ignition source is then applied to it.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] For 20% alcohol by mass (about 25% by volume), this will occur at about 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] The flash point of pure ethanol is 13 °C (55 °F), but may be influenced very slightly by atmospheric composition such as pressure and humidity.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol mixtures can ignite below average room temperature.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is considered a flammable liquid (Class 3 Hazardous Material) in concentrations above 2.35% by mass (3.0% by volume; 6 proof).
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is a byproduct of the metabolic process of yeast.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] As such, ethanol will be present in any yeast habitat.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol can commonly be found in overripe fruit.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol produced by symbiotic yeast can be found in bertam palm blossoms.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Although some animal species, such as the pentailed treeshrew, exhibit ethanol-seeking behaviors, most show no interest or avoidance of food sources containing ethanol.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is also produced during the germination of many plants as a result of natural anaerobiosis.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol has been detected in outer space, forming an icy coating around dust grains in interstellar clouds.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Minute quantity amounts (average 196 ppb) of endogenous ethanol and acetaldehyde were found in the exhaled breath of healthy volunteers.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Auto-brewery syndrome, also known as gut fermentation syndrome, is a rare medical condition in which intoxicating quantities of ethanol are produced through endogenous fermentation within the digestive system.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Ethanol is produced both as a petrochemical, through the hydration of ethylene and, via biological processes, by fermenting sugars with yeast.
[src:butanediol-fermentation/ethanol] Which process is more economical depends on prevailing prices of petroleum and grain feed stocks.
